"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Deuteronomy chapters 1–2
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-deuteronomy-1-2.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/deuteronomy.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/deuteronomy.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/deuteronomy.json (new — no prior entries)

Key Christological decisions:
- Frame narrative (1:1–5): Moses's final speech from beyond the Jordan positions him
  as the lawgiver who cannot himself enter rest. Christ is the new Moses who gives
  the new law (Sermon on the Mount, Matt 5–7) and does enter — and leads others
  into — the eternal rest (Heb 4:8–11).
- Joshua/Yeshua typology (1:38): Joshua's Hebrew name is identical to "Jesus"
  (Yeshua, meaning YHWH saves). Heb 4:8 confirms the typological reading: if
  Joshua had given true rest, the author of Hebrews argues, God would not have
  spoken of another day — Jesus provides the rest Joshua's conquest could not.
- The 70 leaders appointed (1:9–15): The selection of 70 leaders under Moses
  foreshadows Jesus appointing 70 disciples (Luke 10:1); Moses's admission of
  limitation ("I cannot carry you alone") contrasts with Christ who bears all
  burdens and intercedes for all (Matt 11:28–30; Heb 7:25).
- "As a man carries his son" (1:31): YHWH's carrying of Israel as a father carries
  a son is a revelation of divine fatherhood that finds its fullest expression in
  the eternal Father-Son relationship and in Christ bearing the weight of human
  sin (1 Pet 2:24).
- The dying generation (2:14–15): The 38-year period until the unbelieving
  generation died corresponds structurally to the Pauline death-and-resurrection
  pattern: the old self must die before the new life can inherit the promise
  (Rom 6:4–6; Col 3:3–4).
- Sihon's hardened heart (2:30): Like Pharaoh's hardening, this discloses God's
  sovereignty so that his glory is magnified — a pattern Paul expounds in Rom 9:17.
  Christ is the one in whom God's sovereign purposes over history are fully
  disclosed and accomplished.
- Rephaim / giant peoples (2:10–12, 20–22): These ancient peoples represent
  powers Israel could not overcome on its own; YHWH destroys them. Type of
  Christ's defeat of principalities and powers (Col 2:15; Eph 6:12).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DEUTERONOMY = {
  "1": {
    "1": """<p>The opening frame — "these are the words Moses spoke" — sets up Deuteronomy as a farewell speech, the last words of Israel's mediator before he is taken from them. The speech-form itself is a shadow: Moses speaking from beyond the Jordan, unable to enter, points toward the one who will not only speak the word but be the Word (John 1:1), who crosses into rest on behalf of his people.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>Eleven days' journey stands against forty years' wandering — a pointed contrast. The distance from Horeb to Kadesh-barnea was manageable; Israel's disobedience multiplied the cost by forty years. The theme of unnecessary delay through unbelief is fulfilled and reversed in Christ: what the law could not accomplish because of human weakness (Rom 8:3), Christ accomplished, ending the long exile of the human condition.</p>""",
    "3": """<p>The fortieth year, first day of the eleventh month — Moses's speech is carefully dated, marking the end of wilderness wandering as the context for this final address. The fortieth year recalls Moses himself spending forty days on Sinai (Exod 24:18), and Jesus's forty days in the wilderness (Matt 4:1–2). Both are periods of formation before the decisive commission; Christ's forty days end not in failure but in triumph over temptation.</p>""",
    "4": """<p>The defeat of Sihon and Og is noted as the backdrop for Moses's teaching. These victories were accomplished by YHWH's power and established the pattern of divine warfare that characterizes the conquest. Christ's defeat of "every ruler, authority, power, and dominion" (Eph 1:21) is the ultimate fulfillment of this pattern — the final conquest that Sihon and Og's defeat only previewed.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>Moses "began to expound this law" — the verb used is <em>be'er</em>, to make plain or clarify. Moses is not merely repeating Sinai but interpreting it for a new generation. Christ does the same with a greater authority: "You have heard it said... but I say to you" (Matt 5:21–48). Where Moses expounds the law, Christ fulfills and surpasses it (Matt 5:17).</p>""",
    "6": """<p>YHWH's word "you have stayed long enough at this mountain" is a summons to advance. The revelation at Horeb was not meant to be a permanent encampment but the launching point for the journey. Spiritually, Christ does not call his people to remain at Sinai — the law as tutor leads to him (Gal 3:24), and in him the destination is reached, not the mountain.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>The scope of the land promise is expansive: Amorites, Arabah, hill country, lowland, Negeb, seacoast, Lebanon, Euphrates. This geographic breadth corresponds to the Abrahamic covenant (Gen 15:18–21). Gal 3:16 identifies "your offspring" as Christ; the land inheritance broadens in the NT to include all nations (Matt 28:19; Rev 5:9–10) — the land is the type; the new creation is the antitype.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>"The land the LORD swore to your fathers — to Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob — to give to them and to their offspring." Galatians 3:16 reads this promise typologically: the singular "offspring" is Christ, and all who are in Christ are Abraham's seed and heirs of the promise (Gal 3:29). The land grant to the patriarchs was a temporal type of the eternal inheritance secured in Christ (Eph 1:14).</p>""",
    "9": """<p>Moses's admission — "I am not able to carry you by myself alone" — is a confession of the limitation of human mediation. He must share the burden through appointed leaders. Christ as mediator does not share this limitation: he "always lives to make intercession" (Heb 7:25) and is able "to save to the uttermost" all who draw near to God through him. The contrast between Moses's insufficient mediation and Christ's perfect priesthood is developed fully in Hebrews 7–9.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>"As numerous as the stars of heaven" echoes the Abrahamic promise (Gen 22:17; 26:4). The fulfillment of the numerical promise is part of the Christological inheritance: Rev 7:9 depicts "a great multitude that no one could count, from every nation," gathered around the Lamb — the stars-of-Abraham promise fulfilled in those who belong to Christ.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>Moses's blessing-prayer — "may the LORD increase you a thousand times and bless you as he promised" — anticipates the ultimate expansion of the covenant community. Paul prays in similar terms (Eph 3:18–20) for the church to comprehend the fullness of Christ's love; the blessing promised to Abraham is released to all nations through the gospel (Gal 3:8).</p>""",
    "12": """<p>"How can I alone bear your weight, your burden, and your disputes?" — Moses's complaint has the character of a lament over human incapacity for human leadership. Christ in contrast is the one who says "come to me, all who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest" (Matt 11:28); he does not distribute the burden but takes it on himself.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>Moses's instruction to choose "wise, understanding, and experienced men" from the tribes establishes judicial governance under the covenant. The wisdom tradition ultimately points to Christ as "the wisdom of God" (1 Cor 1:24), in whom "are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge" (Col 2:3). The appointed judges are shadows of the one true judge (John 5:22; Acts 17:31).</p>""",
    "14": """<p>Israel's agreement — "the thing you have said is good for us to do" — is a moment of consent to Moses's governance structure. The covenantal dynamic of the people's willingness is fulfilled in the new covenant, where Christ does not impose his rule by force but calls disciples who follow willingly (Ps 110:3; John 10:27).</p>""",
    "15": """<p>The officers appointed — commanders of thousands, hundreds, fifties, and tens — form a hierarchical leadership structure under YHWH. This pattern is echoed in Jesus's sending of the twelve (Matt 10:1) and the seventy-two (Luke 10:1), establishing a new governance of his kingdom that works downward from him through his appointed representatives.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>"Hear the cases between your fellow Israelites and judge fairly between a man and his brother and the foreigner." The inclusion of the foreigner in the judicial charge foreshadows the universality of justice in Christ's kingdom, where "there is neither Jew nor Greek" (Gal 3:28) and the law applies equally. The foreigner's inclusion points toward the Gentile inclusion in the new covenant people.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>"For the judgment belongs to God" — human judges are deputies, not ultimate authorities. Christ is the appointed ultimate judge: "the Father judges no one, but has given all judgment to the Son" (John 5:22). This verse's theology of delegated judgment reaches its terminus in Christ, to whom all judgment is finally and definitively committed (Acts 17:31).</p>""",
    "18": """<p>Moses commanded all the things the people should do — the summary of the law's positive content. Christ's own commandments to his disciples (Matt 28:20, John 13:34–35) build on but transcend Moses: the new commandment to love one another as Christ loved them is given not merely as a legal requirement but as a participation in divine love.</p>""",
    "19": """<p>The journey through "that great and terrifying wilderness" recalls the testing of the people in conditions of danger and scarcity. Jesus's forty days in the wilderness (Matt 4:1–11) recapitulate this journey in condensed form; where Israel tested YHWH throughout the wilderness period, Jesus as the true Israel passed every test, fulfilling what the nation failed to accomplish.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>"The LORD your God is giving us" — present tense of divine gift. The land is given before it is possessed. Christ applies the same logic to salvation: the kingdom belongs to the poor in spirit (Matt 5:3); the inheritance is given, not earned. The indicative precedes and grounds the imperative.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>"Do not fear or be discouraged" — the repeated anti-fear command in Deuteronomy echoes through Joshua and the prophets and reaches its fullest expression in Christ: "Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. Not as the world gives do I give to you. Let not your hearts be troubled, neither let them be afraid" (John 14:27). The Deuteronomic courage command anticipates the peace Christ gives as the ground for courage.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>The people's proposal to send spies was human initiative replacing divine command — YHWH had already said "go up and take possession." The request for intelligence before obedience represents the temptation to substitute human calculation for faith. Christ calls his disciples to obedience without fully worked-out tactical plans: "follow me" (Matt 4:19), not "let me analyze the situation first."</p>""",
    "23": """<p>Twelve men, one from each tribe — the representative sampling of the entire covenant people for the scouting mission. Jesus's twelve disciples represent the reconstituted twelve tribes of Israel (Matt 19:28; Rev 21:12–14), a deliberate echo of Mosaic structure signaling that Christ is establishing a new covenant community in continuity with but surpassing the Mosaic pattern.</p>""",
    "24": """<p>The spies' journey to Eshcol ("cluster of grapes") and the land's fertility points to the Promised Land as a type of the eschatological abundance described in Amos 9:13–14 and Rev 22:2. Christ is the true vine (John 15:1), the source of the spiritual abundance the land only prefigured. The cluster of grapes from Eshcol is an icon of the kingdom's provision.</p>""",
    "25": """<p>"It is a good land that the LORD our God is giving us" — the positive spy report confirms the promise. The good news (gospel) of the land is a prototype: God has prepared a good inheritance, and the report of its goodness calls for belief and advance. The NT gospel is similarly a true report of what God has accomplished and prepared in Christ, calling for faith-response.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>Israel's refusal to go up and their rebellion against YHWH's command is the paradigmatic failure of unbelief — the event Hebrews 3:7–19 dwells on at length as a warning to the church. The writer of Hebrews cites this episode: "Today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts as in the rebellion" (Heb 3:15). The Kadesh failure is the negative example against which Christ's faithful obedience shines.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>"Because the LORD hated us, he brought us out of Egypt to hand us over to the Amorites" — the grumbling misreads YHWH's love as hatred. This distortion of divine character is the opposite of gospel understanding. Paul in Romans 8:32 answers the same question from the other side: "He who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all — how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?" The gift of the Son is the definitive proof that God's action for his people is love, not hatred.</p>""",
    "28": """<p>The report of Anakite giants — "we even saw Anakite giants there" — produced terror that nullified the positive spy report. The Anakim represent the overwhelming power that human strength cannot overcome. Christ conquers by means that human calculations would never choose (1 Cor 1:25–27): the cross appears as defeat but is the site of the decisive victory over all principalities and powers (Col 2:15).</p>""",
    "29": """<p>"Do not be terrified or afraid of them" — Moses's counter-command to fear is grounded in YHWH's presence and past action. Christ's "do not be afraid" (Matt 14:27; John 6:20; Rev 1:17) always comes with "I am" — the divine presence is the ground of fearlessness, and in Christ that presence has taken human form and dwelt among us (John 1:14).</p>""",
    "30": """<p>"The LORD your God who goes before you will himself fight for you" — YHWH as divine warrior going ahead of the covenant people is a central Deuteronomic theme. Christ goes ahead as the "pioneer" (Heb 12:2, <em>archēgos</em> — trailblazer or founding champion) who has already fought and won the decisive battle, and now leads those who follow him into the inheritance already secured.</p>""",
    "31": """<p>"As a man carries his son" — YHWH's patient carrying of Israel through the wilderness is an image of fatherly love expressed in physical proximity and protection. The NT develops divine fatherhood through the eternal Father-Son relationship: God's care for Israel is the temporal expression of the eternal love the Father has for the Son, extended to those who are in Christ (John 17:23). The "man carries his son" image is a time-bound picture of eternal fatherly love.</p>""",
    "32": """<p>"Yet in spite of all this you did not trust the LORD your God" — the indictment of unbelief. Hebrews 3:19 draws the same conclusion about the wilderness generation: "they were unable to enter because of unbelief." Christ is the author and perfecter of faith (Heb 12:2): the one whose own faith (faithfulness) was perfect, and who now mediates faith to those who look to him.</p>""",
    "33": """<p>The pillar of cloud by day and fire by night going before Israel — YHWH's visible guidance through the wilderness. Jesus says "I am the way" (John 14:6), identifying himself with the divine guidance the wilderness pillar provided. The Spirit given at Pentecost (Acts 2:1–4, with fire and wind) is the NT counterpart of the wilderness guidance: the same divine presence taking a new form.</p>""",
    "34": """<p>YHWH's anger at Israel's words is a judicial response to covenant violation — the community's complaints were rejections of YHWH's character and purposes. Christ as mediator absorbs the judicial consequence for human rejection of God (Rom 3:25; 1 John 4:10 — <em>hilasmos</em>, propitiation); his sacrifice addresses not only the formal violation but the personal rupture caused by covenant rejection.</p>""",
    "35": """<p>"Not one of the men of this wicked generation shall see the good land" — the oath of exclusion is the judgment of unbelief. Hebrews uses this exact oath to warn the church: "as I swore in my wrath, they shall not enter my rest" (Heb 3:11; 4:3). The judgment is real; but Christ provides the entry into rest (Heb 4:10) that the wilderness generation forfeited.</p>""",
    "36": """<p>Caleb, who "wholly followed the LORD," is the sole exception among his generation and receives the specific inheritance he scouted. The language of wholehearted following appears in NT discipleship: Jesus calls for followers who do not look back (Luke 9:62), who love him with their whole heart (Matt 22:37). Caleb's undivided loyalty is the type of the wholehearted faith the gospel demands and enables.</p>""",
    "37": """<p>"The LORD was also angry with me on your account" — Moses is excluded from the land partly because of Israel's sin, though the proximate cause is his own failure at Meribah (Num 20:12). The partial solidarity between Moses's exclusion and Israel's sin is a weak type of substitution — imperfect, since Moses was also culpable. Christ's bearing of consequences is true substitution, involving no fault of his own (2 Cor 5:21; 1 Pet 2:22).</p>""",
    "38": """<p>"Joshua son of Nun, who stands before you — he shall go in." Joshua's Hebrew name is <em>Yeshua</em>, "YHWH saves" — the same name as "Jesus" in Greek. Hebrews 4:8 makes the typological connection explicit: "if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken later about another day." Jesus is the true Joshua who leads his people into the rest that the land of Canaan only typified (Heb 4:9–11).</p>""",
    "39": """<p>The children who had "no knowledge of good or evil" will inherit the land — the very ones Israel thought would be prey (v28). This inversion — the helpless inheriting what the strong forfeited — prefigures the kingdom principle Christ articulates: "unless you turn and become like children, you will never enter the kingdom of heaven" (Matt 18:3). The covenant passes to those who receive it as a gift rather than seizing it by human strength.</p>""",
    "40": """<p>The command to turn back into the wilderness is the consequence of unbelief — delay and continued wandering instead of advance into rest. Hebrews 3–4 develops this as a warning against repeating the wilderness generation's error: the offer of rest is real, but it can be forfeited through unbelief. Christ is the one who ensures that those who believe in him do not remain in the wilderness of sin and spiritual exile.</p>""",
    "41": """<p>Israel's presumptuous reversal — "we will go up and fight, just as the LORD our God commanded us" — comes after the moment of divine permission has passed. The law cannot save retrospective obedience; there is a moment, and when it passes, willing compliance with the letter of the command does not recover divine favor. Christ is the one who ensures that the acceptable time does not close on those who come to him: "now is the acceptable time; now is the day of salvation" (2 Cor 6:2).</p>""",
    "42": """<p>"I am not in your midst" — the withdrawal of divine presence is the most catastrophic consequence of disobedience. Israel could not fight without YHWH fighting for them. Conversely, Christ promises "I am with you always, to the end of the age" (Matt 28:20) — the permanent divine presence that makes impossible the kind of abandoned defeat Israel suffered at Hormah.</p>""",
    "43": """<p>Israel's arrogant advance despite the divine veto is the culmination of the unbelief pattern: not trusting YHWH's word in either direction — neither when he said "go up" earlier, nor when he said "do not go up" now. This twofold failure reveals that the problem is not circumstantial reluctance but structural distrust of YHWH. Christ is the one who trusted the Father perfectly — even to the point of death (Phil 2:8).</p>""",
    "44": """<p>The Amorites "chased you like bees" — the rout was total and humiliating. Military defeat outside YHWH's commission is not mere failure but expulsion from divine protection. The same people who had "hearts melting" at Israel's approach (v28) now devastate them. This reversal illustrates that human power without divine commissioning is nothing — a truth Paul applies theologically: "apart from me you can do nothing" (John 15:5).</p>""",
    "45": """<p>Israel "wept before the LORD, but the LORD would not listen" — the closed ear of judgment. Proverbs 1:28–30 and Hosea 5:6 use the same image: a time comes when seeking YHWH finds no answer because the moment of repentance has passed. Christ as high priest ensures that "he is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him" (Heb 7:25), permanently holding open the channel of intercession for those who come.</p>""",
    "46": """<p>"You remained at Kadesh a long time — all those days you stayed there." The extended stay at Kadesh is both punishment and pause before the next chapter of YHWH's purposes. The wilderness period is not mere wandering; it is a purgative sojourn between Sinai and Canaan. Paul uses the wilderness generation as a theological type of the Christian's life between conversion and final inheritance (1 Cor 10:1–11): we too are "in the wilderness" between the Passover of Christ's death and the full possession of the promised inheritance.</p>"""
  },
  "2": {
    "1": """<p>Turning back into the wilderness at YHWH's command frames the wandering years as theologically purposeful rather than aimless. The wilderness is not wasted time; it is the crucible in which faith is tested. Jesus's wilderness period (Matt 4:1–11) replicates this structure in compressed form: the Spirit leads him into the desert for testing, and he emerges ready for the ministry the wilderness prepared.</p>""",
    "2": """<p>YHWH's direct address to Moses — "then the LORD said to me" — preserves the pattern of ongoing divine speech throughout the wilderness. The word of YHWH is the thread through the wandering years, not silence. The Gospel of John opens by identifying Christ with the eternal Word (John 1:1–3), grounding all divine speech in the Son who is himself the final and definitive speech of God (Heb 1:1–2).</p>""",
    "3": """<p>"You have been going around this mountain long enough. Turn north." The divine command to stop circling and begin the forward advance corresponds to the moment of spiritual breakthrough — the transition from extended wilderness sojourn to purposeful advance. For the church, Christ's resurrection is the "turn north" — the end of the sin-and-judgment cycle and the beginning of the new-creation advance (2 Cor 5:17).</p>""",
    "4": """<p>Israel is commanded to pass through Edomite territory with care and respect — the descendants of Esau are "your brothers." The kinship obligation toward Edom establishes that God's purposes do not require the erasure of other nations; the conquest is targeted, not genocidal of all peoples. Christ's mission likewise does not destroy nations but redeems them: "Go and make disciples of all nations" (Matt 28:19), not eliminate them.</p>""",
    "5": """<p>"I will not give you any of their land — not even enough to set a foot on — because I have given Mount Seir to Esau as a possession." God's allocation of lands to non-Israelite peoples (Edom, Moab, Ammon) establishes the theological point Paul makes in Acts 17:26: "from one man he made all nations... and he marked out their appointed times and the boundaries of their settlements." The whole earth is under YHWH's sovereign allocation, a sovereignty fully expressed in Christ as heir of all things (Heb 1:2).</p>""",
    "6": """<p>The command to buy food and water from Edom — to deal commercially, not by seizure — establishes a principle of just commerce with neighboring peoples. The covenant people were not entitled to plunder everyone they encountered. Christ's kingdom ethic similarly involves respect for others' goods and dignity (Luke 3:14; 1 Thess 4:12), not exploitation of others under the banner of divine purpose.</p>""",
    "7": """<p>"The LORD your God has blessed you in all the work of your hands... you have lacked nothing." The providential care over 40 wilderness years — no lack despite the absence of permanent settlement — is the narrative ground for Paul's claim in Phil 4:19: "my God will supply every need of yours according to his riches in glory in Christ Jesus." The wilderness provision is the type; Christ as the source of all supply is the antitype.</p>""",
    "8": """<p>Israel passes by Edom without conflict — the peaceful transit models what covenantal obedience to YHWH looks like in regard to peoples outside the covenant community: restraint, respect, no provocation. The church is called to the same posture toward those outside: "conduct yourselves with wisdom toward outsiders" (Col 4:5); the kingdom does not advance by hostility to non-members.</p>""",
    "9": """<p>YHWH's protection of Moab — "I have given Ar to the people of Lot as a possession" — extends his sovereignty beyond Israel to include the descendants of Abraham's nephew. Ruth the Moabite becomes an ancestor of David and ultimately of Christ (Matt 1:5), demonstrating that Moab's preservation was not merely diplomatic but part of the line that led to the Messiah.</p>""",
    "10": """<p>The parenthetical note about the Emim — the ancient giant peoples who formerly inhabited Moab — establishes a background of primordial powers that preceded the current nations. These Rephaim-class peoples are consistently presented as obstacles that YHWH clears before his advancing covenant purposes. The pattern anticipates Christ's dismantling of the principalities and powers (Col 2:15) that oppose the advance of the gospel.</p>""",
    "11": """<p>The Emim are "counted as Rephaim, like the Anakim" — the tradition of fearsome giant peoples represents the category of human power that appears overwhelming but falls before YHWH. First Corinthians 1:27 — God chose the weak things of the world to shame the strong — is the NT restatement of this pattern: the powers that seem invincible are regularly overcome by divine strategy that confounds human calculation.</p>""",
    "12": """<p>"The people of Esau dispossessed them... just as Israel did to the land of their possession that the LORD gave them." The parenthetical compares Esau's displacement of the Horites with Israel's conquest — God grants lands to peoples and removes prior occupants according to his sovereign purposes. This sovereignty is the background for Paul's argument that God's purposes cannot be thwarted (Rom 8:28–30; 9:6–29): what YHWH purposes in history comes to pass, culminating in Christ.</p>""",
    "13": """<p>The crossing of the Brook Zered marks the transition from the Edomite border southward to the approach of Moab — a geographic waypoint in the advance toward Canaan. Every such crossing is a type of the progressions in redemptive history: from Egypt to Sinai, from Sinai to Jordan, from Jordan to Canaan. Ultimately, Christ's death and resurrection is the final crossing — from the old creation to the new (2 Cor 5:17).</p>""",
    "14": """<p>Thirty-eight years elapsed between Kadesh-barnea and the crossing of Zered — precisely until the fighting generation of unbelievers died out. The long gap is not wasted; it is the judgment falling at the measured pace of YHWH's patience. Peter applies this temporal patience to the church's waiting for Christ's return: "the Lord is not slow concerning his promise... he is patient toward you, not wishing that any should perish" (2 Pet 3:9).</p>""",
    "15": """<p>"The LORD's hand was against them, to destroy them from the camp." The death of the wilderness generation is portrayed as active divine judgment, not merely natural attrition. The same seriousness about sin and its consequences characterizes the NT understanding of judgment: the cross is not a softening of divine justice but its full satisfaction in Christ (Rom 3:25–26). YHWH's hand against sin is answered by Christ bearing the weight of that hand on behalf of his people.</p>""",
    "16": """<p>The death of "all the men of war" marks the completion of a generation. Theologically, this is the type of the death of the "old humanity" that Paul describes in Rom 6:6: "our old self was crucified with him so that the body ruled by sin might be done away with." The old fighting generation must fully die before the new generation can advance under Joshua/Yeshua into the inheritance.</p>""",
    "17": """<p>"The LORD said to me" — the divine word resumes after the long pause of judgment. The resumption of prophetic communication signals the end of the punitive period and the beginning of forward movement. Christ's resurrection similarly breaks the silence of the tomb: the Father vindicates the Son (Acts 2:24; Rom 1:4), and the gospel commission is given (Matt 28:18–20) — the divine word resumes with new authority.</p>""",
    "18": """<p>The command "today you are to cross the border of Moab" — the divine present tense inauguration of the next stage of advance. Every "today" in Deuteronomy carries urgency; the writer of Hebrews applies this urgency directly: "today, if you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts" (Heb 3:7–8). Christ's invitation has the same present-tense urgency: "now is the acceptable time" (2 Cor 6:2).</p>""",
    "19": """<p>Israel is commanded not to harass the Ammonites, another Lot-descended people given their land by YHWH. The pattern of restraint toward peoples outside the specific conquest mandate establishes that YHWH's purposes are particular and targeted, not generalized aggression. The universality of salvation in Christ does not override his specificity of call: he appoints the times and places (Acts 17:26) within which the gospel advances.</p>""",
    "20": """<p>The Rephaim tradition continues: the Ammonites called them Zamzummim. These ancient giant peoples represent the category of power that YHWH repeatedly destroys before his advancing purposes. Ephesians 6:12 identifies the spiritual equivalent: "we wrestle not against flesh and blood, but against principalities, against powers, against the rulers of the darkness of this age" — Christ's cross disarmed these powers (Col 2:15), accomplishing what the conquest of Canaan only typed.</p>""",
    "21": """<p>"The LORD destroyed them before the Ammonites, who dispossessed them and settled in their place." YHWH acts in advance of the human action, clearing the way for those he is establishing. The same pattern governs Christ's work: he goes ahead as the <em>archēgos</em> (Heb 12:2 — pioneer or founding champion), clearing the path through death and resurrection, so that those who follow him walk a path he has already secured.</p>""",
    "22": """<p>The same pattern of YHWH destroying the Horites before the people of Esau is repeated for rhetorical emphasis. The repeated parallels across nations (Edom, Moab, Ammon) establish the cosmic scope of YHWH's sovereignty: he is not merely the God of one nation but the disposer of all nations' lands and peoples. Christ as "heir of all things" (Heb 1:2) and Lord over all principalities and powers (Eph 1:21) fulfills this universal lordship.</p>""",
    "23": """<p>The Avvim, displaced by the Caphtorim (Philistines) — another example of YHWH's sovereign disposal of peoples. Even non-Israelite displacements are within his purview. The Philistines, who will become Israel's great antagonists in the period of the judges and kings, are introduced here. David's defeat of Goliath the Philistine is a type of Christ's defeat of the great adversary (1 Sam 17; Col 2:15).</p>""",
    "24": """<p>"I have given into your hand Sihon the Amorite, king of Heshbon" — the perfect tense of divine gift precedes the actual battle. The victory is declared before it is fought. This is the structure of the NT gospel: the victory over sin and death is accomplished at the cross (Col 2:14–15) before the Christian fights any particular battle. We fight from victory, not toward it — YHWH has already "given" what we are called to take possession of (1 Cor 15:57).</p>""",
    "25": """<p>"This day I will begin to put the dread and fear of you on all peoples under heaven." YHWH's campaign of psychological warfare — establishing Israel's terrifying reputation — prepares the way for the conquest. The spreading of the gospel advances similarly: word of Christ's resurrection spread so that communities were overturned before missionaries arrived (Acts 19:17; Rom 1:8). The fame of Christ precedes and enables the advance of his kingdom.</p>""",
    "26": """<p>Moses sends messengers with "an offer of peace" to Sihon — the formal diplomatic protocol before warfare. The gospel is similarly an offer of peace before judgment: "we implore you on behalf of Christ, be reconciled to God" (2 Cor 5:20). The offer is made in good faith; rejection of the offer does not negate its genuineness. Christ's lament over Jerusalem (Matt 23:37) shows the same sincerity of invitation meeting rejection.</p>""",
    "27": """<p>"I will travel only on the road, turning neither to the right nor to the left" — the peaceful request to pass through without seizure mirrors the Sinai command to Israel to keep the way (Deut 5:32). Christ himself is "the way" (John 14:6) — not merely a route marker but the narrow path (Matt 7:14) that leads to life, requiring those who follow it to travel faithfully without deviation.</p>""",
    "28": """<p>The request for food and water in exchange for money — commercial rather than exploitative — echoes the earlier command regarding Edom (v6). The consistent posture of asking rather than seizing in dealings with non-covenant peoples is a witness to the character of YHWH's community: they do not take what is not given. Christ does not force himself on anyone but stands at the door and knocks (Rev 3:20).</p>""",
    "29": """<p>Moses appeals to Esau's and Moab's precedent — "as they did for me" — as evidence that peaceful transit is reasonable and customary. The appeal to precedent reflects the relational and historical character of covenant ethics: decisions are made in the context of ongoing relationships, not merely abstract principles. The gospel is similarly grounded in historical precedent: "as the Father has loved me, so I have loved you" (John 15:9) — Christ's love is patterned on the eternal Father-Son love.</p>""",
    "30": """<p>Sihon's refusal — "the LORD your God had made his spirit obstinate and his heart stubborn" — introduces the hardening motif that parallels Pharaoh's hardening in Exodus. Paul treats both cases in Romans 9:17–18, arguing that God's hardening of some serves to "make known his power" and "manifest his wrath and power" — and ultimately to magnify the mercy shown to those who receive it (Rom 9:22–24). Christ's cross is the site where this judgment and mercy converge perfectly.</p>""",
    "31": """<p>"I have begun to give Sihon and his land over to you" — again the divine perfect-tense prior gift. "Begin to take possession" is the human correlate to the divine prior action. This is the gospel logic of Colossians 2:12: "having been buried with him in baptism... you were also raised with him." The spiritual reality is established by God's act; the human life is the outworking of what is already true.</p>""",
    "32": """<p>Sihon's forces came out to meet Israel at Jahaz — his own aggression against the peaceful offer seals his fate. The battle is not Israel's initiative but Sihon's. YHWH's judgment falls on those who reject the offer of peace and choose confrontation. The same structure governs Christ's final judgment: those who reject the gospel stand condemned not because the offer was withheld but because it was refused (John 3:18).</p>""",
    "33": """<p>"The LORD our God delivered him over to us" — the passive-causative framing keeps the victory squarely in YHWH's domain. Israel struck the blow, but the deliverance was divine. First Corinthians 15:57: "thanks be to God who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ" — the same structure applies to the final victory over sin and death. The decisive agent is always YHWH/Christ; the human participant shares in a victory that was never theirs to manufacture.</p>""",
    "34": """<p>The total destruction (<em>herem</em>, the devotion-to-destruction ban) of Sihon's cities — men, women, and children — represents the most difficult aspect of the conquest theology. The <em>herem</em> is a form of total consecration to YHWH, a judgment carried out on specific peoples at specific points in redemptive history. It is not a universalizable military ethic. Christ's final judgment (Rev 19:11–21) is the ultimate <em>herem</em> — the decisive clearing of all that opposes God's purposes — but exercised by Christ alone, not by his followers.</p>""",
    "35": """<p>"Only the livestock we took as spoil for ourselves" — the exception to the total destruction reveals that the <em>herem</em> was not a prohibition on all material benefit but a specific devotion of persons to destruction. The provision of spoil to the army continues the pattern of YHWH providing material blessing alongside spiritual commission. Christ's servants are promised both spiritual and material provision (Matt 6:33): "seek first the kingdom... and all these things will be added to you."</p>""",
    "36": """<p>"There was not a city too strong for us" — the comprehensive statement of victory covers the entire range of Sihon's territory. No stronghold resisted. This total effectiveness reflects Christ's complete victory: "I have overcome the world" (John 16:33). Paul's application in Rom 8:37–39 — "in all these things we are more than conquerors through him who loved us" — extends the same comprehensive-victory language to the believer's life in Christ.</p>""",
    "37": """<p>The geographic boundary — Israel did not approach Ammonite territory "whatever the LORD our God had forbidden us" — shows that the comprehensive victory was accompanied by precise obedience to the divine limits. The total effectiveness of YHWH's power did not license expansion beyond the specific command. Christ's victory is total, but his kingdom's advance follows the particular commission given: "to the Jew first and also to the Greek" (Rom 1:16), discipling all nations in the specific sequence and manner he appointed.</p>"""
  }
}


def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'deuteronomy')
    merge_comm(existing, DEUTERONOMY)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'deuteronomy', existing)
    print('Deuteronomy 1–2 mkt-christ written.')


if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
